The CNC/Fe/GQDs chiral nematic film has both structural color and fluorescence response properties in their optical properties. Photographs of the CNC/Fe/GQDs chiral nematic film taken in UV light are shown in Fig. 5d. The blue fluorescence of the chiral nematic film under UV radiation gradually weakened with the increase of benzene gas concentration. Fig. 5e shows the fluorescence intensity of the films gradually decreased with increasing benzene gas concentration. This may be attributed when the adsorbed benzene molecule is radiation by the UV light, the excited electrons on the GQDs are not emitted into the surrounding air. Instead, it is absorbed by the electron-deficient benzene molecule through the conjugated π bond, resulting in the directional transfer of electrons. Finally, the fluorescence of CNC/Fe/GQDs chiral nematic film was quenched [43–45]. Fig. 5f shows the cyclicity capability of the CNC/Fe/GQDs chiral nematic film in response to benzene gas. The benzene reactions of the CNC/Fe/GQDs film shown remarkable reversibility and repeatability in five cycles. When exposed to 75 mg/m3 benzene gas, the Δλ
                        max of CNC/Fe/GQDs fluctuates within 5 nm, and the fluorescence intensity remains stable, indicating that CNC/Fe/GQDs have good reproducibility. Furthermore, the color and fluorescence of the chiral nematic film quickly recovered to the initial state when the film was transferred from the benzene gas environment of 75 mg/m3 to air. Therefore, the impact of benzene gas on the optical properties of the CNC/Fe/GQDs chiral nematic film is reversible. In addition, the benzene gas performance of the CNC/Fe/GQDs chiral nematic film in comparison with other CNC chiral nematic sensing materials (Table 1
                        ). Due to the chemical inertness of benzene gas, the observed color change is not obvious. Therefore, this work provides a promising strategy for CNC colorimetric sensor to detect benzene gas.

The developed CNC/Fe/GQDs chiral nematic material displays predominant gas response performance, therefore, we construct a smartphone-based response network system for signal transformation. To do so, we design the RGB chromaticity program of color array based on the above-mentioned response results of CNC/Fe/GQDs chiral nematic films under benzene gas (Fig. 10
                        ). All color arrays are converted into the corresponding RGB value, and thus, the RGB value is transformed into Gray value (Y) coordinates [58]. As expected, the consistence of Y and the concentration of the benzene displays a strong linear relationship (Fig. S6 and S7). The concentration of benzene gas ranged from 0 to 125 mg/m3 with a relationship coefficient (R

                           2
                        ) of 0.93575. The fitted equation was Y = 11.93C + 1.16, where Y and X denote the gray value (Y) and benzene gas content, respectively. Similarly, the correlation coefficient (R

                           2
                        ) of benzene gas concentration in the range of 0–75 mg/m3 in the fluorescence response analysis is 0.86444. The fitted linear equation was Y = 9.71C + 1.29.
